        <text>Transient dynamics of an altered large marine ecosystem
</text>
      </sentence>
    </passage>
    <passage>
      <offset>56</offset>
      <infon key="type">body</infon>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">2</infon>
        <offset>56</offset>
        <text>Overfishing of large-bodied benthic fishes and their subsequent population collapses on the Scotian Shelf of Canada's east coast and elsewhere resulted in restructuring of entire food webs now dominated by planktivorous, forage fish species and macroinvertebrates.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">3</infon>
        <offset>321</offset>
        <text>Despite the imposition of strict management measures in force since the early 1990s, the Scotian Shelf ecosystem has not reverted back to its former structure.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">4</infon>
        <offset>481</offset>
        <text>Here we provide evidence of the transient nature of this ecosystem and its current return path towards benthic fish species domination.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">5</infon>
        <offset>617</offset>
        <text>The prolonged duration of the altered food web, and its current recovery, was and is being governed by the oscillatory, runaway consumption dynamics of the forage fish complex.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">6</infon>
        <offset>794</offset>
        <text>These erupting forage species, which reached biomass levels 900% greater than those prevalent during the pre-collapse years of large benthic predators, are now in decline, having outstripped their zooplankton food supply.
</text>
        <annotation id="T1">
          <infon key="type">Decrease</infon>
